{
  "doc_id": "26229",
  "text": "Brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) is the most widely distributed neurotrophin and is involved in neurogenesis, differentiation, survival and synaptic plasticity [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). BDNF secretion is activity-dependent-e.g. increased by cognition and exercise, and decreased by stressors-and modulates neurotransmission in dopamine, glutamate, gamma-aminobutyric acid and serotonin systems (e.g. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The human BDNF gene encodes a 247 amino acid pre-protein (pro-BDNF) that is cleaved to form an evolutionarily conserved 120 amino acid mature protein [CITATION_6] . A single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP; rs6265) results in methionine substitution for valine at codon 66 (Val 66 Met). The evolutionarily recent, less-frequent Met allele alters the pro-BDNF protein sequence, which disrupts trafficking and results in less activity-dependent BDNF secretion without affecting the mature BDNF sequence [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
